					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Leather scroll of the 15th century. </p>
						<objectDesc form="scroll ">
							<supportDesc material="leather">
								<support>Leather. </support>
								<extent>42 membranes, 226 columns. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
										<height>455</height>
										<width>2510/7210</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<collation>
									<p>42 membranes, with leather wrapper and canvas ties. </p>
								</collation>
								<condition>
									<p>Surface dirt ingrained in leather.
</p>
									<p>Some mould and/or salt accretions. </p>
									<p>Edges slightly horny in places. </p>
									<p>Damp staining at edges. </p>
									<p>Slight usage stains.
</p>
								</condition>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="226" ruledLines="51" writtenLines="51">
									<p>Uniform layout. </p>
									<p>Ruling by hard point,
membrane by membrane.</p>
									<p>Visible pricking and stitching. </p>
									<p>226 columns in total, three to six columns per membrane, 51 lines per column. </p>
									<p>No tagin present. The letter ḥet arched throughout. </p>
									<p>Exodus, Leviticus, Numbers and Deuteronomy begins with a new column, four lines being left at the end of the preceding column. </p>
									<p>Every column commences with a new verse, most frequently beginning with the letter ו. </p>
									<p>The end of a verse marked by a dry point after the last word (omitted at the end of a section and column). </p>
									<p>אתנח indicated by a dry point under the word. </p>
									<p>An upper dry point distinguishes between את, כל, הוא and את-, כל-, הוא-. </p>
									<p>Three dry points sometimes in the margin at the beginning of an open or closed section. </p>
									<p>Special arrangement of lines of the Song of Moses. </p>
									<p>Majuscular and minuscular letter in accordance with the rules. </p>
									<p>The reversed letter nun is placed before and after Num. 10:35-36; &apos;pe lafuf&apos; is very frequent. </p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
